# Tries in Java

A Trie (pronounced 'try', from re**trie**val) is a tree where **each edge represents one character** and **each node represents a prefix**. Walking from the root to any node spells out a prefix. Walking to a node marked as a word-end spells out a complete word. This structure makes prefix queries — 'does anything start with XY?' — O(length of prefix), regardless of how many words are stored.

## Node structure and shape
```java
// Each node has up to 26 children (one per lowercase letter)
// and a boolean flag marking 'a word ends here'.
//
// Visualise inserting 'cat', 'car', 'dog':
//
//        root
//       /    \
//      c      d
//      |      |
//      a      o
//     / \     |
//    t*  r*   g*     (* = isEnd true)
//
// 'ca' is a prefix but NOT a word (isEnd=false at 'a' node)
// 'cat' IS a word  (isEnd=true  at 't' node)

class TrieNode {
    TrieNode[] children = new TrieNode[26];  // index = ch - 'a'
    boolean isEnd = false;
}
```

## Insert — walk the path, create nodes on demand
```java
class Trie {
    private final TrieNode root = new TrieNode();

    void insert(String word) {
        TrieNode cur = root;
        for (char ch : word.toCharArray()) {
            int idx = ch - 'a';
            if (cur.children[idx] == null)
                cur.children[idx] = new TrieNode();  // create if missing
            cur = cur.children[idx];
        }
        cur.isEnd = true;  // mark the final node as a complete word
    }
}
// Time: O(L)  where L = word length
// Space: O(L) new nodes in worst case
```

## Search vs startsWith — spot the one-character difference
```java
// SEARCH: does the FULL word exist?
boolean search(String word) {
    TrieNode cur = root;
    for (char ch : word.toCharArray()) {
        int idx = ch - 'a';
        if (cur.children[idx] == null) return false;  // prefix broken
        cur = cur.children[idx];
    }
    return cur.isEnd;  // ← must be a complete word
}

// STARTSSWITH: does any stored word begin with this prefix?
boolean startsWith(String prefix) {
    TrieNode cur = root;
    for (char ch : prefix.toCharArray()) {
        int idx = ch - 'a';
        if (cur.children[idx] == null) return false;
        cur = cur.children[idx];
    }
    return true;  // ← just reaching the node is enough, no isEnd check
}
```

## Autocomplete — collect all words under a prefix node
```java
List<String> autocomplete(String prefix) {
    TrieNode cur = root;
    for (char ch : prefix.toCharArray()) {
        int idx = ch - 'a';
        if (cur.children[idx] == null) return Collections.emptyList();
        cur = cur.children[idx];
    }
    // DFS from 'cur' collecting all words
    List<String> results = new ArrayList<>();
    dfs(cur, new StringBuilder(prefix), results);
    return results;
}

void dfs(TrieNode node, StringBuilder sb, List<String> res) {
    if (node.isEnd) res.add(sb.toString());
    for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
        if (node.children[i] != null) {
            sb.append((char)('a' + i));
            dfs(node.children[i], sb, res);
            sb.deleteCharAt(sb.length() - 1);  // backtrack
        }
    }
}
```

## When Trie beats HashMap
| Operation | HashMap | Trie |
|---|---|---|
| Exact word lookup | O(L) avg | O(L) |
| Prefix existence | O(total words × L) | O(L) |
| Autocomplete | O(total words × L) | O(L + output) |
| Sorted word iteration | O(n log n) | O(n) in-order DFS |

**Use Trie when:** you need prefix queries, autocomplete, spellcheck, or IP routing.
**Use HashMap when:** only exact lookups and inserts — simpler and lower constant factors.

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting cur.isEnd = true after the loop in insert — the word is stored as a path but not marked as a complete word
- Confusing search() and startsWith() — search requires isEnd=true; startsWith just needs the path to exist
- Using HashMap<Character, TrieNode> as children — correct but slower than TrieNode[26]; use array for lowercase-only alphabets
- Not backtracking the StringBuilder in DFS autocomplete — causes words to accumulate incorrectly
- Assuming delete is simple — deleting a word may require removing shared prefix nodes only if no other word uses them

## Connections
- **Strings**: every Trie operation processes one character at a time — O(L) where L is string length
- **Hashing**: Trie is an alternative to HashMap<String,...> when prefix queries matter
- **Recursion/Backtracking**: autocomplete DFS uses backtracking (StringBuilder undo)
- **Graphs/Trees**: a Trie is a rooted tree — DFS traversal collects all stored words
